The equation is given in the form $z^2 = r\text{e}^{\theta\text{i}}$. We first identify the modulus $r$ and the argument $\theta$ from the right-hand side.

$$
\begin{aligned} 
z^2 &= 4\text{e}^{\frac{\pi}{2}\text{i}} \\ 
r &= 4 \\ 
\theta &= \frac{\pi}{2} 
\end{aligned}
$$

To find the square roots, we take the square root of the modulus and divide the argument by 2. For the second root, we add $\pi$ to the new argument (since roots are separated by $\frac{2\pi}{n}$).

**Modulus for roots:**
$$|z| = \sqrt{4} = 2$$

**Arguments for roots:**
$$
\begin{aligned} 
\theta_1 &= \frac{\frac{\pi}{2}}{2} = \frac{\pi}{4} \\ 
\theta_2 &= \frac{\pi}{4} + \pi = \frac{5\pi}{4} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Now we convert the first root from polar form $z_1 = 2\text{e}^{\frac{\pi}{4}\text{i}}$ to Cartesian form using the formula $z = r(\cos\theta + \text{i}\sin\theta)$.

$$
\begin{aligned} 
z_1 &= 2\left(\cos\frac{\pi}{4} + \text{i}\sin\frac{\pi}{4}\right) \\ 
&= 2\left(\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} + \text{i}\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right) \\ 
&= \sqrt{2} + \text{i}\sqrt{2} 
\end{aligned}
$$

Similarly, we convert the second root $z_2 = 2\text{e}^{\frac{5\pi}{4}\text{i}}$ to Cartesian form.

$$
\begin{aligned} 
z_2 &= 2\left(\cos\frac{5\pi}{4} + \text{i}\sin\frac{5\pi}{4}\right) \\ 
&= 2\left(-\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} - \text{i}\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right) \\ 
&= -\sqrt{2} - \text{i}\sqrt{2} 
\end{aligned}
$$

The calculator displays the roots in Cartesian form (or exact form on CAS models):

$$
\begin{aligned} 
z &\approx 1.414... + 1.414...\text{i} \\ 
z &\approx -1.414... - 1.414...\text{i} 
\end{aligned}
$$
